Our third iteration of the Sydney Millions Series wrapped up in the early hours of Tuesday morning â€” and after 24 hours to reflect, we couldnâ€™t be prouder of what this series became.

ğŸ’¼ A Huge Thank You To...

Our dealers, TDs, admin, and back-of-house staff â€“ your hard work and professionalism make these events run seamlessly.

Our media team â€“ Jamie Hall, Matthew Marshall, and Chris Wadih â€“ who, for the first time, brought the Sydney Millions to the big screen!

Our wonderful venue partners, St. George Leagues Club, for working tirelessly with us to provide such a fantastic environment.

And of course, our amazing players â€“ your energy, sportsmanship, and good vibes are what make this series truly special.

ğŸ¯ Looking Ahead

We now set our sights on February 2026 for our next Series, and before that, all attention turns to Kings Poker, who will host the final Kings Cup of the year in early December.

Jenna Lo does the double! After taking down the Ladies Event earlier this week, Jenna was still riding the high as she closed in on her second title within the same series.

The Closing Event drew 93 entries, and Jenna battled all the way through to heads up against Frank Loannidis. The pair agreed to an even chop and played it out for the trophy, with Jenna coming out on top to secure the double.

An amazing effort and a huge achievement, congratulations Jenna on pulling off this tough and memorable feat!

Another strong turnout for our midweek $10K GTD at Wenty Leagues, with 95 entries taking their seats in pursuit of the top prize.

Congratulations to Jin and Abdul for your heads-up deal and to the rest that cashed tonight.

The final APLPT Main Event for 2025 has come to a close after a rollercoaster series of events.

Almost half of the final table was spent four-handed, with play lasting an astonishing 113 minutes.

It took just two hands to go from our top three to a champion, giving Daniel Handley ample time to celebrate the win here at the SS&A Club in his hometown of Albury.

It comes as his first APL title, and first poker trophy, in the only event he managed to play this series.

Daniel began a new job on Monday, and spent the majority of the week training down in Melbourne. It came at the cost of not being able to enter any other tournaments.

â€œI would usually play the crap out of these (series),â€ he laughed post-win.

He used his 380 Poker Tour Credits (PTC) alongside $80 of his own cash to play this event, from which he has now turned into more than $25,000 worth of prizes, including a seat into the 2026 APL Million.

In 2022 Daniel won a satellite entry into the APL Million Main Event, where he placed 62nd for a cash of over $5,600, which until tonight was his best live cash.

Reflecting on this win, he remarked heâ€™s usually the king of being coolered, and a result like this was â€œA long time comingâ€.

Daniel was joined by runner-up and fellow Albury poker regular Raymond Barrett, who also won his way into the Main Event cheaply, turning a $55 satellite entry into a $460 ticket, and then into a score of almost $16,000 cash plus an APL Million Main seat as well.

What a wonderful result for Albury, congratulations to all who found success in this Main Event, and we canâ€™t wait to bring it back here in 2026!

It was another huge Sunday for us today at Queen B's Poker in our crowd favourite Sunday Deepstacks. With another triple figure field and a $8,120 prize pool. A big congratulations to Daniel Eastaway on getting his first win with us and Andrew Bond both gents playing a great final table and taking home over $2k each for their $80 entry. There's not many games where you can win 25 x your buy-in every week for 1st and 2nd.

Ladies and Gentlemen, please join us in congratulating your new Sydney Millions 2025 Main Event winner, Hannah Lee!

This series has been an amazing ride as we were, for the first time, able to watch many of our marquee events unfold live on stream. Catching most of the action from Day 2, we got to see a huge amount of Hannah at the table as she put on a masterclass of consistency, patience and perfectly timed aggression.

Hannah refused to let herself be bullied and constantly picked up on her opponentsâ€™ weaknesses, capitalising when it mattered and putting herself in stronger positions throughout.

After a slow burn with around 16 runners, play started to move quickly as we approached the final table. Hai Keeâ€™s unconventional tactics threatened to take Hannah out on a couple of occasions, but thanks to her awareness she got it in good and held when she needed to.

The final table was a long battle that pushed into the early hours, but well over 100 viewers stayed locked into the stream to see how it ended at the ripe old time of 4:30am this morning.

Heads up, very late, and with a very even 35 bigs each, Hannah and Gavin made a few murmurs about a deal, but both decided to play it out till the very end. 

In the second to last hand, fate would side with Hannah as the pair get it in pre flop with Hannahâ€™s QQ taking on Gavins TT. In a perfect piece of poker poetry, the â€˜ladiesâ€™ held and Hannah would lock up her career-best score of $178,500 in the next hand. 

Hannah had taken a break from poker for a few years, but a couple of months ago decided it was time to get back into it. Since then sheâ€™s been finding results almost instantly, and this one will be a win sheâ€™ll never forget.

Congratulations Hannah, and to everyone who cashed in this record-breaking Main Event.

Michael Matthews began his poker journey with APL back in 2005, and over the majority of the following decade he turned semi-pro and found a string of solid results, including multiple titles for PLO and mixed game events, and amassed winnings of over $110,000 in that time.

His last Hendon Mob entry was back in 2014, until this week. Michael ended his hiatus and made the trip here to Albury from his home in Ballarat, and has played every day since Tuesday. 

In his first ever APLPT, he bagged in the Classic, cashed in the Main, and made the final table of the Big Bounty Hunter. Due to other events overlapping, he couldnâ€™t play in his preferred game, PLO, until today.

He has his first title and trophy in over a decade, and now says he might be ready for a comeback on a more regular basis!

Steve Cappelluto does it twice in the same year! Back in Februaryâ€™s Main Event, Steve locked up $25,000 in a four-way even chop, but this time heâ€™s gone even better.

Steve, Michael, and Stewie agreed on an ICM chop but took $1,000 off each, leaving $3k and the trophy to play for. First, Stewie would fall, then heads-up Michael Pham shoved and Steve decided to call it off blind. He turned over Aces!

The bullets held and the rest is history. Steve secured another $3k, bringing his total haul to $47,615 and, of course, the bragging rights of taking down a Main Event with a trophy to prove it.

Congratulations to all who cashed, and well played Steve!

content:
NEW WEEKLY SHCEDULE WITH BIG CHANGES!

This Thursday we will run our $1,000 freeroll for qualifiers who played 5 games with us. Then starting from Thursday 11/12/25 our Thursday Turbo Deepstack will now be a $100 Dealer-Dealt tournament!

The other exciting dealer change is that we have replaced our Saturday Dealer-Dealt game with a cheaper $150 Mystery Bounty! 

Our Social late night games will now be satellites into our $150 and $350 dealer dealt games giving all of our players the opportunity to play it big. All payouts in socials will be $150 or $350 tickets or B'S BUCKS for places that don't pay the full ticket amount. These will not expire and can be used in any tournament of the value you win.

Lastly we have made the tough decision to increase the buy-in of our crowd favourite our Sunday Deepstacks. This is moving to a $95 entry (including $15 admin fee). We need to increase the admin-fee to help cover the costs of putting on such an amazing Sunday poker tournament for everyone.

We hope players are excited by these big changes. It will take us a few days to update our website to match. We look forward to a big December of poker with you all.

#QueenBsPoker #BuildTheBuzz #QLDPoker #WeeklySchedule

HIGOR'S GOT HEAPS IN THE $10K WC WARM-UP
The second largest buy-in event on the schedule, the $10k WPT World Championship Warm-Up, drew a stellar crowd of 58 entries.

23 of these players managed to find their way to Day 2 today, with Higor Seibel bagging the chip lead.

Full chip counts and seat allocations below.

The top 8 players will finish in the money, with the winner to take home almost $200k:

1st - $196,199 + WPT Prime Championship ticket
2nd - $115,268 
3rd - $72,213 
4th - $49,050 
5th - $38,150 
6th - $29,975 
7th - $24,525 
8th - $19,620 

Play will get back underway at 12.30pm today, with blinds at 10,000 / 20,000 (20,000).

Guests must be aged 18 years or over to enter the casino. Player Activity Statements are available on request from the Guest Service Desk, via The Star App or our Website. Help is close at hand. GambleAware gambleaware.nsw.gov.au 1800 858 858

Mackenzie Alford took the chip lead into The Centurion final table yesterday, and has emerged with the title today!

His first series on the APL Poker Tour came in August at the APL Million, where he took the silverware in the 6-Max Shot Clock and found a couple of other deep runs to collect more than $100,000 in total winnings.

It came shortly after he made the move across the Tasman from his home in New Zealand, when he burst onto the scene at PlayLive Melbourne in June and then proceeded to win six tournaments and make over $60,000 in the space of two months. 

After his first APL title, Mackenzie told us: â€œIâ€™ll be spending some more time in Australia!â€

Heâ€™s living here now and has travelled to Albury, returning to APL for his second series with us, and he has continued his superb run with another victory on the big stage. 

Mackenzie said post-win that he felt terrific. He loved the structure of the tournament, adding, â€œIâ€™m a fan of the playability.â€

He also said it was his first time playing poker on a cards-up live stream, but promised himself heâ€™d try not to change his aggressive style of play. 

â€œI played my best when I didnâ€™t worry about it (viewers seeing his hands) and played my natural game.â€

For now itâ€™s time for a quick breather after the three-day grind, and then itâ€™s straight into the $150,000 Jackstar Super High Roller!

Congratulations Mackenzie!

Stephen Smith has his second APLPT title, and has achieved a new high score with a win in the Monster Stack!

He won the NLH 6-max in Albury back in March, and today takes over $13,000 plus an APL MIllion Main Event seat.

Stephen spoke of his scores so far this series, having run deep in both the Main Event and the Jackstar, despite not finding many strong hands. He relied on grinding away at winning small pots without showdown to find modest cashes but not going as far as hoped.

His luck changed tonight, going on to become the last player to leave the APLPT room for 2025!

A special shoutout to Jarrod Thatcher, who entered the FT with the shortest stack (280k), which he managed to spin up to almost the same value in cash.

Ben Yang is the newest name to be added to the esteemed list of Jackstar champions!

With play set to pause for the night due to venue closure time, an all-in and call managed to find us a winner without needing to return the next day.

He faced fierce competition throughout the night, with David Bowen dominating play from the moment the field reached the money until midway through the final table. Lara Jones was the clear short stack, yet spun it up to a chip lead throughout a marathon three-handed stage of the tournament.

At heads-up, Ben not only faced Fred Tschirsch , but Fred's entire rail - vocal with support for every move Fred made.

The Melburnian was relieved, but exhausted, letting us know it was his best live cash from any tournament, before happily heading off to bed!

Congrats, Ben!

INTRODUCING YOUR CHAMPIONSHIP EVENT FINAL TABLE
After three Day 1 flights and 600 total entries, the 2025 WPT Australia Championship Event has reached its official final table, led by Jordan Bautista.

Full chip counts and seat allocations below. 

We'll update this post with the final table photo once the players arrive this morning after a well-deserved rest.

Along with being immortalised in history on the WPT Mike Sexton Champions Cup, there is plenty of prizemoney up for grabs too:
1st - $558,211 + WPT World Championship entry (worth $16,000) 
2nd - $371,693 
3rd - $273,928 
4th - $203,971 
5th - $153,458 
6th - $116,656 

Play will get back underway today at 11.30am, with the live-stream available on this page, our Twitch channel, and on WPT's channels from approximately 12.00pm, where we will play down to a winner. Final table commentary to be provided by none other than Tony Dunst.  

Guests must be aged 18 years or over to enter the casino. Player Activity Statements are available on request from the Guest Service Desk, via The Star App or our Website. Help is close at hand. GambleAware gambleaware.nsw.gov.au 1800 858 858

It was one of the latest (or earliest) events in Churchillâ€™s history, with 5 players still remaining and hovering around 15 bigs each at 4:20am. Shortly after the posted video, players discussed an ICM deal that would have leveled out the payouts to about $10k each.

Some were keen, but Nancy wanted to continue and play it out, while David, the slight short stack at the time, was adamant about earning more points for Player of the Series. In the end, no unanimous decision was reached.

It was an amazing spin-up, Koray entered the final table with literally a quarter of a big blind and spun it up to hundreds of thousands in chips, laddering all the way into 5th place. An incredible feat.

David managed to climb a couple more spots, earning extra valuable Player of the Series points, before the final two, Kevin and Shengfeng, eventually agreed to an ICM chop.

Shengfeng has an outstanding record at the Kings Room but had never taken a title at Churchills, so he was overjoyed to finally add a new venue trophy to his cabinet.

Congratulations to all who cashed, thank you to the players who came down to build this record-breaking prize pool, and well played Ma!

Hala, Sergio!

Across the two week festival, more than $9 million was played for, and won on our tables â€“ making this the largest festival EVER held in NSW.

Secondly, Karen Chen - the Ladies Australian Championship winner, who took home the title and $18,069 in prize money while only having played poker for a total of two weeks in her lifetime!

â™ ï¸ Wenty Leagues Wednesday â™ ï¸

A little extra value was up for grabs tonight at our $10K GTD at Wenty Leagues, with 69 entries hitting the felt and chasing over $3,000 up top for that midweek boost heading into the weekend.

With the top 8 set to be paid, the final table showed great sportsmanship by agreeing to pay the bubble, ensuring everyone who made it that far went home with something. The action was fast and furious â€” the final table wrapped up in under 90 minutes, with five eliminations in the first half hour!

Congratulations to Mahmoud, who battled through the field to take down the win and pocket just shy of $3,000 in cash and prizes.

A special shoutout to Silas, a new face to our Wenty game, who kindly stood in for the winnerâ€™s photo after finishing 4th in his debut run. Great to see new players joining the action â€” and we hope to see even more next week for our $10K GTD Wednesday at Wenty Leagues!

In what must be one of the biggest comebacks in Kings Room history, Kamyar Ekrami takes down The Big Stack. Heads up with no deals discussed, Kamyar was down to less than two big blinds. With just four individual chips in front of him and a tower in front of his opponent, the event looked all but over.

But in poker, youâ€™re never out of the race until the last chip has been swallowed. Kamyar went on an incredible run, doubling over and over again until he was the one with the tower and all the chips in play.

This incredible turn of the tides earned him just shy of an additional $7,000 a brilliant story on the penultimate night of the Sydney Millions.
